---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---

<Base
  title="Thermodynamics Concepts | Nuclear Rankine Cycle"
  activeNav="concepts"
  description="Key thermodynamics concepts for the Rankine cycle: enthalpy, entropy, steam quality, exergy, and second law efficiency."
>

  <!-- ── Page Hero ── -->
  <div class="page-hero" style="background:#0891B2;">
    <div class="inner">
      <p class="hero-eyebrow">Foundation</p>
      <h1>Thermodynamics Concepts</h1>
      <p class="hero-sub">
        The thermodynamic vocabulary you'll need throughout this guide. Skim the familiar sections.
        Read the exergy and second-law sections carefully. Most intro courses skip them entirely.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ── Enthalpy ── -->
  <div class="sec-banner" style="background:#1865F2;">
    <h2 class="inner">Enthalpy</h2>
  </div>
  <div class="content-row">
    <div class="inner concept-layout">
      <div class="concept-body">
        <p>
          Enthalpy represents the total heat content of a substance by combining internal energy
          and the energy required to make room for it at a given pressure and volume (Pv). This
          simplifies engineering calculations for open systems by accounting for flow work.
          Otherwise, you would need to account for pressure and specific energy in every
          calculation separately.
        </p>
        <div class="eq-block">
          <span class="eq-label">Specific Enthalpy</span>
          <span class="eq-expr">h = u + Pv</span>
          <span class="eq-units">[kJ/kg]</span>
        </div>
        <p>
          Every device in the Rankine cycle operates at steady state with continuous flow in and
          out. Thermodynamicists call these <strong>steady-state, steady-flow (SSSF)</strong>
          devices. For these devices, neglecting kinetic and potential energy changes, the first
          law reduces to:
        </p>
        <div class="eq-block">
          <span class="eq-label">SSSF Energy Balance</span>
          <span class="eq-expr">q &minus; w = h<sub>out</sub> &minus; h<sub>in</sub></span>
          <span class="eq-units">[kJ/kg]</span>
        </div>
        <p>
          This is why steam tables list enthalpy directly. h<sub>in</sub> and h<sub>out</sub>
          are the only thermodynamic quantities needed to compute heat transfer and work across
          every Rankine cycle component.
        </p>
      </div>
      <aside class="concept-links">
        <p class="links-label">Learn More</p>
        <a class="concept-link" href="https://www.britannica.com/science/enthalpy" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Britannica: Enthalpy &rarr;</a>
        <a class="concept-link" href="https://webbook.nist.gov/chemistry/fluid/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">NIST Webbook: Steam Properties &rarr;</a>
      </aside>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ── Entropy ── -->
  <div class="sec-banner" style="background:#0891B2;">
    <h2 class="inner">Entropy</h2>
  </div>
  <div class="content-row content-row--bg">
    <div class="inner concept-layout">
      <div class="concept-body">
        <p>
          Entropy is a measure of the unavailability of energy to do useful work. More precisely,
          it captures how much energy in a system is spread out or dispersed in a way that cannot
          be recovered as work. For a reversible heat transfer &delta;q at absolute temperature T,
          the change in specific entropy is:
        </p>
        <div class="eq-block">
          <span class="eq-label">Clausius Definition</span>
          <span class="eq-expr">ds = &delta;q<sub>rev</sub> / T</span>
          <span class="eq-units">[kJ/kg&middot;K]</span>
        </div>
        <p>
          An entropy balance on any system or control volume takes the form:
        </p>
        <div class="eq-block">
          <span class="eq-label">Entropy Balance (Rate Form)</span>
          <span class="eq-expr">dS/dt = &Sigma;(Q&#775;<sub>k</sub> / T<sub>k</sub>) &minus; m&#775;<sub>out</sub>s<sub>out</sub> + m&#775;<sub>in</sub>s<sub>in</sub> + S&#775;<sub>gen</sub></span>
        </div>
        <p>
          The term S&#775;<sub>gen</sub> &ge; 0 by the second law. It equals zero only for
          reversible processes and is strictly positive whenever irreversibilities are present.
          This includes friction, heat transfer across a finite temperature difference, and mixing.
        </p>
        <p>
          For a reversible, adiabatic <strong>(isentropic)</strong> process, &Delta;s = 0.
          The ideal turbine and pump in the Rankine cycle are both treated as isentropic.
          A real turbine has s<sub>out</sub> &gt; s<sub>in</sub>, indicating lost work potential.
        </p>
      </div>
      <aside class="concept-links">
        <p class="links-label">Learn More</p>
        <a class="concept-link" href="https://www.britannica.com/science/entropy-physics" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Britannica: Entropy &rarr;</a>
        <a class="concept-link" href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/engineering/entropy" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">ScienceDirect: Entropy &rarr;</a>
      </aside>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ── First Law / Energy Equation ── -->
  <div class="sec-banner" style="background:#16A34A;">
    <h2 class="inner">First Law — The Energy Equation</h2>
  </div>
  <div class="content-row">
    <div class="inner concept-layout">
      <div class="concept-body">
        <p>
          For a steady-state, steady-flow system with one inlet and one outlet, neglecting kinetic
          and potential energy changes, the rate form of the first law is:
        </p>
        <div class="eq-block">
          <span class="eq-label">SSSF First Law</span>
          <span class="eq-expr">Q&#775; &minus; W&#775; = m&#775; (h<sub>out</sub> &minus; h<sub>in</sub>)</span>
        </div>
        <p>
          Dividing by mass flow rate gives the per-unit-mass form:
          q &minus; w = h<sub>out</sub> &minus; h<sub>in</sub>. Applied to each component of the
          Rankine cycle (covered in detail in the
          <a href={`${base}basic-rankine-cycle`}>Basic Rankine Cycle</a> section):
        </p>
        <div class="component-table">
          <div class="ct-header">
            <span>Component</span>
            <span>Process</span>
            <span>Balance (per kg)</span>
          </div>
          <div class="ct-row" style="border-left-color:#1865F2;">
            <span><strong>Pump</strong> (1&rarr;2)</span>
            <span>Adiabatic, isentropic compression</span>
            <span>w<sub>p</sub> = h<sub>2</sub> &minus; h<sub>1</sub> &nbsp;<em>(work in)</em></span>
          </div>
          <div class="ct-row" style="border-left-color:#EA580C;">
            <span><strong>Boiler</strong> (2&rarr;3)</span>
            <span>Isobaric heat addition</span>
            <span>q<sub>in</sub> = h<sub>3</sub> &minus; h<sub>2</sub> &nbsp;<em>(heat in)</em></span>
          </div>
          <div class="ct-row" style="border-left-color:#16A34A;">
            <span><strong>Turbine</strong> (3&rarr;4)</span>
            <span>Adiabatic, isentropic expansion</span>
            <span>w<sub>t</sub> = h<sub>3</sub> &minus; h<sub>4</sub> &nbsp;<em>(work out)</em></span>
          </div>
          <div class="ct-row" style="border-left-color:#0891B2;">
            <span><strong>Condenser</strong> (4&rarr;1)</span>
            <span>Isobaric heat rejection</span>
            <span>q<sub>out</sub> = h<sub>4</sub> &minus; h<sub>1</sub> &nbsp;<em>(heat out)</em></span>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h3>Applying the SSSF equation to a turbine</h3>
        <p>
          A turbine is well-modeled as adiabatic (Q&#775; &approx; 0, since heat losses through the
          casing are negligible compared to the shaft work). Applying the SSSF first law with
          Q&#775; = 0:
        </p>
        <div class="eq-block">
          <span class="eq-label">Adiabatic Turbine</span>
          <span class="eq-expr">w<sub>t</sub> = h<sub>in</sub> &minus; h<sub>out</sub></span>
          <span class="eq-units">[kJ/kg]</span>
        </div>
        <div class="concept-example">
          <p class="example-label">Example — Turbine work</p>
          <p>
            Steam enters a turbine at h<sub>3</sub> = 2,800 kJ/kg and exits at
            h<sub>4</sub> = 2,100 kJ/kg. The turbine is adiabatic. Shaft work produced per kg:
            <strong>w<sub>t</sub> = 2,800 &minus; 2,100 = 700 kJ/kg</strong>.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="diagram-placeholder">
          <p class="diagram-placeholder-label">Turbine diagram</p>
          <p class="diagram-placeholder-sub">Diagram coming soon</p>
        </div>

        <h3>Thermal efficiency</h3>
        <p>
          Thermal efficiency answers a simple question: what fraction of the heat you put in do you
          get back out as useful work? It follows directly from the component balances:
        </p>
        <div class="eq-block">
          <span class="eq-label">Thermal Efficiency</span>
          <span class="eq-expr">&eta;<sub>th</sub> = w<sub>net</sub> / q<sub>in</sub> = (w<sub>t</sub> &minus; w<sub>p</sub>) / q<sub>in</sub> = 1 &minus; q<sub>out</sub> / q<sub>in</sub></span>
        </div>
      </div>
      <aside class="concept-links">
        <p class="links-label">Learn More</p>
        <a class="concept-link" href="https://www.britannica.com/science/thermodynamics" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Britannica: Thermodynamics &rarr;</a>
        <a class="concept-link" href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/engineering/first-law-of-thermodynamics" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">ScienceDirect: First Law &rarr;</a>
      </aside>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ── T-s Diagram ── -->
  <div class="sec-banner" style="background:#0F2147;">
    <h2 class="inner">The T-s Diagram</h2>
  </div>
  <div class="content-row content-row--bg">
    <div class="inner concept-layout">
      <div class="concept-body">
        <p>
          The T-s diagram is the most powerful visualization in power plant analysis. It plots
          temperature T against specific entropy s for every state point in the cycle. The area
          enclosed by the cycle on a T-s diagram equals the net specific work output
          (w<sub>net</sub> = w<sub>turbine</sub> &minus; w<sub>pump</sub>). The area under the
          upper process curve equals heat added. The area under the lower curve equals heat
          rejected. Efficiency is literally visible as a ratio of areas.
        </p>
        <p>
          The curved boundary shown below is the <strong>saturation dome</strong>. Inside it, liquid
          and vapor coexist. To the left of the dome's peak is compressed liquid. To the right is
          superheated vapor. The peak of the dome is the critical point (374.14&deg;C for water).
        </p>
        <div class="chart-container">
          <canvas id="tsChart"></canvas>
        </div>
        <p>
          The basic Rankine cycle traces a closed path. Process 1&rarr;2 is the pump
          (isentropic, nearly vertical at low s). Process 2&rarr;3 is boiler heating followed by
          vaporization at constant pressure. Process 3&rarr;4 is the turbine (isentropic, vertical
          at high s). Process 4&rarr;1 is the condenser (heat rejection at constant temperature).
          The chart above shows a representative BWR cycle with a condenser at 40&deg;C and
          boiler saturation temperature at 285&deg;C.
        </p>
      </div>
      <aside class="concept-links">
        <p class="links-label">Learn More</p>
        <a class="concept-link" href="https://webbook.nist.gov/chemistry/fluid/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">NIST Webbook: Steam Data &rarr;</a>
      </aside>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ── Steam Quality ── -->
  <div class="sec-banner" style="background:#EA580C;">
    <h2 class="inner">Steam Quality</h2>
  </div>
  <div class="content-row">
    <div class="inner concept-layout">
      <div class="concept-body">
        <p>
          When liquid water and steam coexist inside the two-phase (wet steam) region on a T-s
          diagram, quality x describes what fraction of the total mass is vapor:
        </p>
        <div class="eq-block">
          <span class="eq-label">Steam Quality</span>
          <span class="eq-expr">x = m<sub>g</sub> / (m<sub>f</sub> + m<sub>g</sub>)</span>
          <span class="eq-units">[0 &le; x &le; 1]</span>
        </div>
        <p>
          x = 0 is saturated liquid. x = 1 is saturated vapor (dry steam). Any thermodynamic
          property in the two-phase region interpolates linearly with quality:
        </p>
        <div class="eq-block">
          <span class="eq-label">Wet Steam Properties</span>
          <span class="eq-expr">h = h<sub>f</sub> + x &middot; h<sub>fg</sub> &emsp; s = s<sub>f</sub> + x &middot; s<sub>fg</sub></span>
        </div>
        <p>
          where h<sub>fg</sub> = h<sub>g</sub> &minus; h<sub>f</sub> is the enthalpy of
          vaporization (2,260 kJ/kg for water at 100&deg;C and atmospheric
          pressure<sup><a href="#ref-1" class="cite">[1]</a></sup>).
        </p>
        <div class="callout callout--warn">
          <div class="callout-icon">!</div>
          <div class="callout-body">
            <strong>Turbine blade erosion</strong>
            <p>
              Steam quality below roughly 0.85 causes serious, accumulating damage. Liquid
              droplets at turbine blade tip velocities act like sandblasting: they erode blade
              leading edges over time, reducing turbine efficiency and eventually requiring costly
              replacement. This is the primary engineering reason a simple Rankine cycle cannot
              be used directly in nuclear plants and the main motivation for the reheat cycle.
              More detail is in the <a href={`${base}reactor-turbine-materials`}>Reactor &amp;
              Turbine Materials</a> section.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <aside class="concept-links">
        <p class="links-label">Learn More</p>
        <a class="concept-link" href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/engineering/steam-quality" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">ScienceDirect: Steam Quality &rarr;</a>
      </aside>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ── Exergy ── -->
  <div class="sec-banner" style="background:#7C3AED;">
    <h2 class="inner">Exergy</h2>
  </div>
  <div class="content-row content-row--bg">
    <div class="inner concept-layout">
      <div class="concept-body">
        <p>
          Energy is conserved. But not all energy is equal. Steam at 300&deg;C can produce far
          more useful work than the same joule count of thermal energy at 60&deg;C.
          <strong>Exergy</strong> captures this difference. It measures a thermodynamic state's
          actual ability to produce work relative to the local environment.
        </p>
        <p>
          Formally, flow exergy is the maximum useful work extractable as a fluid stream
          equilibrates with its dead state at temperature T<sub>0</sub> and pressure P<sub>0</sub>:
        </p>
        <div class="eq-block">
          <span class="eq-label">Specific Flow Exergy</span>
          <span class="eq-expr">&psi; = (h &minus; h<sub>0</sub>) &minus; T<sub>0</sub>(s &minus; s<sub>0</sub>)</span>
          <span class="eq-units">[kJ/kg]</span>
        </div>
        <p>
          where h<sub>0</sub> and s<sub>0</sub> are properties of water at ambient conditions.
          For a nuclear plant, T<sub>0</sub> is the outdoor air temperature.
        </p>
        <h3>Exergy vs. energy</h3>
        <ul class="concept-list">
          <li>
            <strong>Exergy is destroyed, not just transferred.</strong> Every irreversible
            process permanently destroys exergy. Energy is conserved. Exergy is consumed.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Exergy destruction = T<sub>0</sub> &middot; S&#775;<sub>gen</sub>.</strong>
            Entropy generation and exergy destruction are two ways of measuring the same
            inefficiency.
          </li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Heat exchanger exergy</h3>
        <p>
          For a heat exchanger transferring heat from a hot fluid to a cold fluid, the second
          law efficiency compares how much exergy the cold side gains to how much the hot side
          loses:
        </p>
        <div class="eq-block">
          <span class="eq-label">Heat Exchanger Second Law Efficiency</span>
          <span class="eq-expr">&eta;<sub>II,HX</sub> = &Delta;&psi;<sub>cold</sub> / &Delta;&psi;<sub>hot</sub></span>
        </div>
        <p>
          Even for an adiabatic, ideal heat exchanger (where every joule leaving the hot side
          enters the cold side), &eta;<sub>II,HX</sub> &lt; 1. All energy is transferred, but the
          ability to do useful work is reduced because the transfer occurs across a temperature
          difference. The irreversibility is fundamentally thermodynamic, not mechanical.
        </p>

        <h3>Second law efficiency for a thermal power plant</h3>
        <p>
          For a thermal power plant, second law efficiency compares net work output to the exergy
          supplied by the heat source:
        </p>
        <div class="eq-block">
          <span class="eq-label">Second Law Efficiency (Plant)</span>
          <span class="eq-expr">&eta;<sub>II</sub> = W&#775;<sub>net</sub> / &Psi;&#775;<sub>in</sub></span>
        </div>
        <p>
          This is a more honest measure of plant performance than first law efficiency alone,
          because it accounts for the quality of the heat being used, not just its quantity.
        </p>
      </div>
      <aside class="concept-links">
        <p class="links-label">Learn More</p>
        <a class="concept-link" href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/earth-and-planetary-sciences/exergy" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">ScienceDirect: Exergy &rarr;</a>
        <a class="concept-link" href="https://www.britannica.com/science/thermodynamics/Thermodynamic-potentials" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Britannica: Thermodynamic Potentials &rarr;</a>
      </aside>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ── Second Law Efficiency ── -->
  <div class="sec-banner" style="background:#DC2626;">
    <h2 class="inner">Second Law Efficiency</h2>
  </div>
  <div class="content-row">
    <div class="inner concept-layout">
      <div class="concept-body">
        <p>
          Thermal efficiency (first law efficiency) tells you how much of Q<sub>in</sub> becomes
          useful work:
        </p>
        <div class="eq-block">
          <span class="eq-label">Thermal Efficiency</span>
          <span class="eq-expr">&eta;<sub>I</sub> = W<sub>net</sub> / Q<sub>in</sub></span>
        </div>
        <p>
          This is intuitive but incomplete. A 33% thermal efficiency might be excellent or poor
          depending on the temperature limits. The upper bound for any heat engine operating
          between a source at T<sub>H</sub> and a sink at T<sub>L</sub> is the
          <strong>Carnot efficiency</strong>:
        </p>
        <div class="eq-block">
          <span class="eq-label">Carnot Efficiency</span>
          <span class="eq-expr">&eta;<sub>Carnot</sub> = 1 &minus; T<sub>L</sub> / T<sub>H</sub></span>
          <span class="eq-units">[T in Kelvin]</span>
        </div>
        <p>
          No real heat engine can exceed this. <strong>Second law efficiency</strong> normalizes
          the actual thermal efficiency against what thermodynamics says is achievable at those
          temperature limits:
        </p>
        <div class="eq-block">
          <span class="eq-label">Second Law Efficiency</span>
          <span class="eq-expr">&eta;<sub>II</sub> = &eta;<sub>I</sub> / &eta;<sub>Carnot</sub></span>
        </div>
        <p>
          A perfectly reversible Carnot cycle has &eta;<sub>II</sub> = 100%. Real plants fall below
          this due to irreversibilities in every component. The gap between &eta;<sub>I</sub> and
          &eta;<sub>Carnot</sub> is where all meaningful thermodynamic improvement lives.
        </p>
        <div class="callout callout--info">
          <div class="callout-icon">i</div>
          <div class="callout-body">
            <strong>Why second law efficiency matters for nuclear plants</strong>
            <p>
              A nuclear plant at 33% thermal efficiency is actually operating at roughly
              50&ndash;60% second law efficiency because its relatively low steam temperatures
              constrain &eta;<sub>Carnot</sub>. First law efficiency makes it look inefficient
              compared to a gas turbine at 40%. Second law efficiency shows it is performing well
              within its physical constraints.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <aside class="concept-links">
        <p class="links-label">Learn More</p>
        <a class="concept-link" href="https://www.britannica.com/science/Carnot-cycle" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Britannica: The Carnot Cycle &rarr;</a>
        <a class="concept-link" href="https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/engineering/second-law-efficiency" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">ScienceDirect: Second Law Efficiency &rarr;</a>
      </aside>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ── References ── -->
  <div class="sec-banner" style="background:#4B5563;">
    <h2 class="inner">References</h2>
  </div>
  <div class="content-row content-row--bg">
    <div class="inner">
      <ol class="refs-list" id="references">
        <li id="ref-1">Lemmon, E. W., Bell, I. H., Huber, M. L., &amp; McLinden, M. O. (2023). <em>NIST Chemistry WebBook, SRD 69: Thermophysical Properties of Fluid Systems.</em> <a href="https://webbook.nist.gov/chemistry/fluid/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">webbook.nist.gov</a></li>
        <li id="ref-2">Borgnakke, C., &amp; Sonntag, R. E. <em>Fundamentals of Thermodynamics</em> (10th ed.). Wiley.</li>
      </ol>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ── Continue ── -->
  <div class="sec-banner" style="background:#0F2147;">
    <h2 class="inner">Continue</h2>
  </div>
  <div class="content-row">
    <div class="inner next-step">
      <p>
        With these concepts in hand, you are ready to explore why the Rankine cycle is the
        standard solution for converting heat into electricity, and which industries depend on it.
        Or if you want to get right into the cycle itself, jump to the Basic Rankine Cycle section.
      </p>
      <div class="next-links">
        <a href={`${base}why-rankine`} class="btn-primary">Why the Rankine Cycle? &rarr;</a>
        <a href={`${base}basic-rankine-cycle`} class="btn-outline">Basic Rankine Cycle (coming soon)</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

</Base>

